Why can ISIS persist?
NEW YORK—The deadly terrorist attacks in Istanbul, Dhaka, and Baghdad show that ISIS's reach has extended to Europe, North Africa, the Middle East, and Asia.
The longer ISIS remains strong in Syria and Iraq, the longer its terrorist network will be able to carry out such massacres.
But ISIS is not particularly difficult to eliminate.
The problem is that the countries involved in Iraq and Syria, including the United States and its allies, have not made ISIS their primary enemy.
This should have changed.
ISIS has a small fighting force; US estimates put their numbers at 20,000 to 25,000 in Iraq and Syria, and around 5,000 in Libya.
In comparison to the active military forces in Syria (125,000), Iraq (271,500), Saudi Arabia (233,500), Turkey (510,600), and Iran (523,000), ISIS is negligible.
In September 2014, US President Barack Obama vowed to "strike and ultimately defeat" ISIS, but the US and its allies, including Saudi Arabia, Turkey, and Israel (behind the scenes), have focused on toppling Syrian President Bashar al-Assad.
Recently, Israeli Army Brigadier General Herzi Halevy bluntly stated (as relayed to me by a journalist present at his speech): "Israel does not want to see the situation in Syria unfold with ISIS defeated, superpowers withdrawing from the region, and Hezbollah and Iran emerging as stronger powers facing Israel."
Israel opposes ISIS, but its greater concern is Iran backing Assad.
Assad allows Iran to support Israel’s two main quasi-military adversaries – Hezbollah and Hamas.
Therefore, Israel’s focus is on toppling Assad rather than defeating ISIS.
Influenced by neoconservatism, for the US, the Syrian war is a continuation of the global American hegemony plan proposed by Defense Secretary Richard Cheney and Deputy Secretary of State Paul Wolfowitz at the end of the Cold War.
In 1991, Wolfowitz told US General Wesley Clark:
"But we did learn one thing from the Gulf War: we can use force in the region – in the Middle East – without the Soviets stopping us."
We have about 5 to 10 years to clean up the old Soviet regimes – Syria, Iran (as originally stated), Iraq – before the next superpower challenges us.
The United States' multiple wars in the Middle East – Afghanistan, Iraq, Syria, Libya, etc. – were to oust the Soviets and subsequently the Russians from competition and establish American hegemony.
These 'efforts' have been devastating failures.
For Saudi Arabia, and for Israel, the primary goal is to overthrow Assad to weaken Iran.
Syria is part of a large-scale proxy war between Shia Iran and Sunni Saudi Arabia, which is playing out on battlefields in Syria and Yemen, and along more intense Shia-Sunni fault lines in countries like Bahrain and other prostrate states in the region that lean toward either side.
For Turkey, toppling Assad would strengthen its regional position.
But Turkey now faces three opponents on its southern border: Assad, ISIS, and nationalist Kurds.
So far, ISIS has been less important to Turkey than Assad and the Kurds.
But ISIS-led terrorist attacks against Turkey could change this dynamic.
Russia and Iran also pursue their own regional interests through proxy wars and support for militias.
But both are prepared to cooperate with the US to fight ISIS, and can work together on other issues as well.
To date, the US has been indifferent because its focus is on toppling Assad.
The US foreign policy establishment condemns Russian President Putin's support for Assad, while Russia accuses the US of trying to overthrow him.
These complaints seem contradictory but are not.
The US and its allies' attempt to overthrow Assad violates the UN Charter, while Russia's support for Assad upholds Syria's right to self-defense as stipulated in the charter.
Indeed, Assad is a dictator, but the UN Charter does not grant any country the power to choose which dictator to overthrow.
The persistent existence of ISIS highlights three strategic flaws and one fatal tactical flaw in American foreign policy.
Firstly, neoconservatism, which demands regime change as a means to achieve American hegemony, is not only ignorant hubris; it is also the classic imperialism overreaching itself.
Wherever the US has tried this approach, it has always ended in failure.
Syria and Libya are the latest examples.
Second, the CIA has long funded secret operations through Saudi Arabia that arm and train Sunni extremists.
In turn, these extremists gave rise to ISIS, which was a direct (and perhaps unintended) consequence of the same policy pursued by the CIA and its Saudi collaborators.
Third, viewing Iran and Russia as irreconcilable enemies to the United States is largely a self-fulfilling prophecy that is outdated.
A rapprochement with both countries is possible.
Fourth, at the tactical level, the US attempt to fight on two fronts against Assad and ISIS has failed.
Whenever Assad is weakened, Sunni extremists, including ISIS and Al-Nusra Front, will fill the vacuum.
If the US, Russia, Saudi Arabia, and Iran provide air cover and logistical support, Assad and his Iraqi allies can defeat ISIS.
Of course, Assad will continue to rule; of course, Russia will remain Syria’s ally; of course, Iran will gain influence there.
Terrorist attacks will undoubtedly continue, perhaps for a while still under the ISIS banner; but the organization will be driven out of its bases of operations in Syria and Iraq.
This result not only can eliminate ISIS from the Middle East; it can also lay the foundation for more comprehensive relief of regional tensions.
The US and Russia can start reversing the new Cold War by jointly driving out jihadist terrorism.
(NATO's commitment to not allowing Ukraine into the alliance or upgrading ballistic missile defenses in Eastern Europe could also be beneficial.)
There are other benefits.
Collaborating against ISIS would give Saudi Arabia and Turkey reasons and opportunities to seek new pragmatic arrangements with Iran.
Israel's security can be strengthened by fostering cooperative economic and geopolitical relations with Iran, which could increase the chances of a lasting peace agreement between Israel and Palestine.
The rise of ISIS reflects strategic flaws in the current Western approach, particularly that of the United States.
The West can defeat ISIS.
The question is whether the US will undertake the necessary strategic reassessment to achieve this goal.
